## Game Master Guidance

### Deciding Use Requirements

Set consistent standards for what counts as bonding use:

**Lenient:** Any meaningful use in dangerous situation (faster bonding, more generous)
**Standard:** Successful uses that materially affect outcomes (balanced progression)
**Strict:** Only critical successes or extraordinary circumstances (slow bonding, high value)

Most campaigns use Standard—successful uses during actual challenges, not practice or trivial circumstances.

### Balancing Bonding

Equipment bonding shouldn't overshadow other advancement:

**Appropriate bonding speed:** 10-15 uses per tier (sessions 5-8 reach Bonded)
**Too fast:** Familiar at session 1, Legendary by session 4 (devalues progression)
**Too slow:** Still working toward Familiar at session 10 (feels unrewarding)

Typical combat-focused campaign: weapon reaches Familiar (session 2-3), Trusted (session 5-6), Bonded (session 8-9), Legendary unlikely unless campaign extends past session 12.

### Unique Properties

When equipment reaches Legendary, collaborate on appropriate unique property:

**Reflect usage:** Sword used for executions might gain bonus against prone enemies
**Match theme:** Armor worn by protector might grant bonus when defending allies
**Balance power:** Unique properties should feel special without overshadowing legendary techniques

Legendary bonding represents 100+ successful uses—significant campaign investment deserving meaningful reward.

### Losing Bonded Equipment

Bonded equipment lost or destroyed creates narrative opportunity:

**Temporary loss:** Quest to recover becomes personal mission
**Destruction:** Reforging quest using pieces maintains bonding (starts at previous stage -1)
**Replacement:** New equipment starts bonding from scratch (old bonds don't transfer)

Don't casually destroy bonded equipment—it represents player investment. But occasional loss creates dramatic stakes.

